*Key takeaways:*

i) Full-length Diagnostic Test in adherence to the GRE exam format

iii) The simulated testing environment at our Manipal branch

iv) Complementary study material and mock tests will be provided

*Timing*: 6:00 pm to 8:30 pm
*Venue*: Collegepond Office, Shantala Lodge building, Manipal, Karnataka 576104. 
Landmark: Near Cafe Coffee Day, Opp. MIT.

24/11/2018, 02:25 - Dikshita Kothari: All the details over various confirmed sources we're put together. 
And the entire scene yesterday was found out chronologically,  most rumours that are spreading are because of misinformation and I'm hoping to resolve at least some of those. 
If you disagree with me or think some fact is wrong,  I'm sorry about that but this is what I believe and you are we come to your own belief. 


1. The original incident occurred at 2:30-3:00 and when first reported,  it wasn't taken seriously.  The girl was told to write a letter about what happened and explain the details. But by this time the culprit had left the campus and gotten away. 

2. The girl and 2 of her brothers from college,  followed  the culprit to Mahindra City but he was able to get away.  Hearing about this and worried for their safety,  a group of 2nd-4th years went behind them to Mahindra City. 

3. The next occurrence was that the hostel girls started gathering at about 7:00 PM.  At this time the Registrar had arrived and tried handling it in a proper manner, however this failed and people started gathering around the registrar and shouting. There had been no North-South comment *at this time * by the Registrar. 
The North South comment was made by the wardens, whose details were noted by everyone including name and the students were informed that they would not be there ever again and specific action will be taken against them.

4. The registrar who wanted to help was intimidated or worried by people's response and left. The girl's hostel gates were closed around 8:00-8:30.  Girls started climbing over the walls in an attempt to stop the registrar, but he was scared and left. 

5. The original girl's complaint was being pushed away, so everyone went instead to the house of the Director of Campus Life, who is the old man that went through the crowd. They gathered near his house and wanted to talk in a rational manner.  However this was proving unsuccessful due to the mass of the crowd,  thus a suggestion was made that everyone should go to the auditorium and talk it out peacefully. 

6.At this point the main gate guards moved into campus to help get the Director to the auditorium. This left the main gates unmanned and allowed outsiders who found out about the scene to enter and cause extra chaos for their own benefit.  
The original victim girl was still at the Director's house so they could get to the auditorium slowly and not get stuck in between the crowd. 

7. The Director moving from the girl's hostel to the auditorium is the scene that most people are aware of and while moving he was constantly surrounded by people and the whole crowd was heaving from random sides due to the right spacing. 
The Director was at this point annoyed and asked why the students were attacking him and that he was not in the ultimate authority and just wants to help.

8.The crowd kept pushing and becoming restless and an incident occured where people tried hitting him. The seniors tried protecting him and because he was old and they also wanted this to be handled in a civil matter as that was the only way they could be assured of a solution. 

9. At this point the Director started abusing, and made the comment regarding ‚Äúwhy do you wear short clothes‚Äù and other things, thus enraging the crowd. The close circle around said Director knew what was happening and most of the peripheral mass had no idea of the details. Thus the presence of the crowd was not helping and anyone on site knows how it was just chaos and pushing. 

10. The crowd was chanting and wanted immediate justice such as bringing the culprit and demanding action be taken on spot. This was however an unreasonable request from someone who had no power over it. 

11. The director took shelter in a security room near the hospital where he made the North South comment due to fatigue.
The security room was attacked after this and the window glass was broken as people tried to enter. 
The students keeping him safe found a way to slowly escort him till the M block through a back entrance.

12. The Director of Student Affairs (DSA head)  made an appearance and entered the college from the front entry along with the SRO, wardens and security guards.  She waited and listened to all the complaints not just the original victim's. She got mad for some reason at one point and so did the group of girls talking to her. 

13. The Director told the victim to file the FIR And get it done with and to write it in her own words- the girl had as of then not written the FIR yet due to her personal reasons. Maybe because she wanted to wait for her parents, the actual reason is unconfirmed. The director asked her to file an FIR and it has been filed now. Proof of this will be presented soon. They don't have a copy available right now. 

14. It was said that precautions will be taken from then onwards so that such an instance does not occur again and the only way to prove it would be to wait and see if they actually follow up in the future. 
The girl herself has currently filed an FIR and while she may not be happy with how long it took and how it was done, she understands that the college is backing her and is okay with the position. 

Official news report-
The report that was said correlating the exam postponement and the girl's case was taken by an NDTV reporter who was outside campus at the gate and could not enter.  They received all their information from students leaving the college, students who had shown up to see what is happening, heard scarce details from others and were now leaving all of whom were 100% boys and lacked actual data. Along with them, the security guards at the gates who were completely unaware about what was happening provided the reporter their data.  As far as the guards were concerned, earlier the same day a protest was made due to the exams and to postpone them and after that about the girl's issue. The reporter heard all this and scourged up a story from what they could piece together.

[22/01, 8:06 AM] Dikshita Kothari: So current in any resistor is divided into two parts complex and real as in a+ib 
The real part of current = a 
The complex part of current = b 
Only the real part adds to the power of the resistor while the complex part reduces it. Real part is constant while complex is variable. 
Imagine you're the resistor. 
Each person in your life can and should be divided into two sections. Complex and real. 
Anyone who contributes to your life in any way and adds to you as an individual is a real person. Anyone who adds to your problems is complex. You should keep the real people carefully and not pay attention to the complex components. Or the real people are your "friends" and the complex people are your "colleagues". 
Not only people this is applicable to everything in your life. Anything fixed is real and anything variable is complex. 
Each night before you sleep you have to make a list. Three things that are real and three things that are complex. 
For example: You can think of pizza as real and a pimple as complex. 
Pin the real components in your life and know how they contribute to you. The complex components are just holding you back as an individual, they're temporary and should be removed.

29/01/2019, 06:42 - Dikshita Kothari: I'm sure their answer will be wrong and stupid
29/01/2019, 06:50 - Dikshita Kothari: There is a phrase that I'm working on eliminating from my vocabulary, and it's one that we all use too frequently. When analyzing the potential compatibility between ourselves and a suitor, oftentimes, the "he's out of my league" excuse comes into play. He (or she) is too tall, too attractive, too smart, too funny, too ambitious or just too plain awesome to be interested in you, right? Wrong. I've come to the realization that no one is truly "out of my league," and here's why.

Let's get this straight: this is no self-serving, pretentious piece proclaiming my alluring charm and dashing good looks. Nope, not at all. I still struggle with my body image issues and self-esteem just like many others do. But I've realized how a iterating simple phrase can become a concept that we really buy into and believe -- we contribute to damaging our self-perception.

The problem is, when we say that someone is "out of our league," we begin believing it. I used to say that guys were out of my league all the time.

"He's too handsome and I'm so average."


"He's hilarious and outgoing; my awkward and goofy sense of humor is no match."

I put myself down despite the other redeeming qualities I have. I viewed my worth as based on how attractive other people thought I was. You can say you don't do this, but you probably do. When we're rejected by someone, we never say, "It must be because I have a really awesome future ahead of me and I'm a really motivated person." No. It's always something along the lines of, "I guess I am not hot enough/fit enough/fun enough/smart enough" for this person's attention.

Even when the situation doesn't apply to ourselves, we apply the method of thinking that people are grouped into leagues. I, too, am guilty of sitting with friends (or hey, even people-watching by myself) and seeing a couple go by with one very attractive partner and one average or "below-average" partner while thinking, "Wow, how did they end up together?"

As someone who genuinely strives to be pro-heathy body image and  socially conscious, I realize that I'm contributing to a huge problem in a way that I never realized. I am equating myself and others to a subjective sense of beauty and worth that can't be standardized or wholly assessed by anybody. No one can determine who is in a certain league, because leagues don't exist.
29/01/2019, 06:50 - Dikshita Kothari: When someone says that you can say this

20/02/2019, 07:31 - Jenit Jain: Task - Write python code to perform feature extraction from a set of audio signals. The audio signals are human speech and features to be extracted are given : - 

* duration : Total duration of the audio
* IntensityMin : Minimum Intensity of the audio signal
* intensityMax : Maximum Intensity of the audio signal
* shimmer : Shimmer is used as one of the measures for the micro-instability of vocal cord vibrations.
* numPause : Number of Pauses
* maxDurPause : Maximum Duration of Pauses
* avgDurPause : Average Duration of Pauses
* TotDurPause : Total Duration of Pauses
* Engaging tone : how much the voice is engaging
* Not Stressed : stress level from the voice

Model will be judged based on the accuracy on the testing data and usage of state of the art architectures. Submit it by 26th February.

Provide a README file along with the code and test in a new virtual environment before submitting.
After completing the screening task mail your code as a zip file at novaturient.ai@gmail.com and resume.

We have received many queries regarding the dataset for feature extraction task. We are providing a few examples from our testing data which would help you in precisely extracting features. 
Google Drive Link :- https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1mTHkngU97IdJXoC8sAVVUg0_xgWKbSGg?usp=sharing

Today we'll tell you a spicy story. üòâ

 *Spices* üßÇü•´
You will all be visiting a spice garden. Spices enhance the colour, fragrance and flavour of food. Spices have many health benefits.  Tell Mamma to feed you Cinnamon buns today. Tasty! üòãü•êüçûü•ñ

 *Ceylon tea* üçÉüå±
Sri Lanka has the perfect ecosystem for growing high-quality tea. We will be volunteering at a tea plantation, plucking leaves and learning  how tea is processed and packaged. ‚òï

 *Strawberries* üçìüçì
We will visit a strawberry farm in Nuwara Eliya where succulent strawberries grow plenty in open fields and poly tunnels. üèù

 *Quest* :
Scroll down to find the official state symbol of ‚ÄúFine Quality Ceylon Tea‚Äù certified by the Sri Lanka Tea Board. The quest for this weekend is to sketch this lion logo, colour it as you please, sign it and post on this group. üìù‚úèüñçüñå

 *Trivia* : ‚ùì‚ùì
1. Name any three exports of Sri Lanka.

No road is long with good company.  And difficult roads often lead to beautiful destinations. It was a long drive but worth it. 

We are settled comfortably in our rooms. Our resort is very picturesque -  spacious log cottages skewed around a giant lawn.  I'm sharing a room with Krishiv and Samriddh. Krishiv has finished his scrap book work for the day and is exploring  the WiFi password of the resort. Samriddh is giving the finishing touches. 

We had a yummy lunch at Pizza Hut. On the bus we caught up on our beauty sleep. And then we played games - 
Volleyball without a ball
Two truths and one lie! 
Head Up Vocal
Heads Up Actions

Manasvi and Kanishk were jammed plenty. 

Yana is the captain of the team 'The Order of the Phonix' and Meghomala is heading 'The Superiors'. 

The day belonged to the Order. But tomorrow is another day. 

All the kids have downloaded the App Your hour to track their phone usage. Three of the older, prettier, more handsome young adults(names withheld on request) who had more than 3 1/2 hours online logs have been punished. They will be the water carriers tomorrow when we scale the daunting Lion Rock. 

Meghomala and Krishiv won the prizes for being the lightest travellers. On a long journey, even a feather weighs like stone. I can't wait to hear the water carriers' experiences tomorrow! 

Tomorrow's plan is 6, 7 and 8 am. 

Powerpacks devoured, Dinner ingested.  Lying like sloths in our Travelicious t-shirts. Savouring the day gone by. 

I'm already beginning to trust this journey. 

Until tomorrow...

01/04/2019, 06:33 - Dikshita Kothari: Hari Om
Animals are such agreeable friends - they ask no questions, they pass no criticisms. 

But what if the animal is a 6 ft long, fat python! 

We had many close, wild encounters today. As we ascended the Lion Rock, a monkey made off with Yana's Tang. Later, we chanced upon the Kingdom of Monkeys but couldn't retrieve the lost belongings. A swarm of bumble bees hovered at a safe distance. We were asked to speak in hushed tones, lest we attract their attention. Dogs followed us in the hope of getting scraps from the lip-smacking power packs. A giant python slid across the kids' shoulders and necks. A cobra danced for the kids' cameras with it's hood open and left the kids spell bound. A tusker elephant stood patiently on the roadside allowing our bus to pass. A herd of deer gambolled amongst the Polonnaruwa ruins. A most unexpected visitor during dinner was a majestic owl and we went click click again. 

Meghomala has a way with dogs. They listen to her. Watching her, I realized that until one had loved an animal, a part of the soul remains unawakened. Krishiv video chats with his dog everyday. 

But the heroes of the day were Palakh and Jayesh. They sailed through the MasterChef and JAM challenges admirably. For a debut, their corn bhel was so authentic, it would have put Bombay Shiv Sagar to shame. 

After three UNESCO world heritage sites, the body was tired. But we decided to swim with our hearts. Muskan, Manasvi and Yana are ace swimmers, their strokes decisive and fluid. They won every race. 

Phone usage has dropped drastically from an average of 3 1/2 hours to 37 minutes. Perhaps, corporal punishment does reform. But the winner was Samriddh who refused to talk to his mother lest his phone show a shameful log entry. 

The Superiors won 'Mind Boggling Lateral Thinking'.  But tomorrow is another day. 

I'm sure everyone is dreaming of elephants at the moment. 

Shhhh.....

02/04/2019, 18:30 - Dikshita Kothari: Hari Om 

Punctuality is the courtesy of Kings. Eight girls couldn't keep to the 6-7-8 am time schedule this morning and were punished. They were made to dance for the more punctilious. 

But it takes all kinds to make the world an interesting place. 

We visited the Millennium Elephant Foundation, the Iswarya Ayurvedic Spice Garden and relished an ethnic 
cultural show at Kandy theatre. Thereafter, we were transported in a shuttle to the magnificent Serendip Stone Bungalow. A swim and a sumptuous dinner were followed by filing away  memories for retrieval at a later date and a strategy game of Battleships. 

All in a day's work. 

I'm privileged to be the raconteur of our adventures but nothing I write will do justice to today's experiences. They were incredible.  

Besides,  a video is worth a thousand words. 

Be punctual please. We'll find a way to reprimand you but we cannot recycle the wasted time ever. 

Blessed....

03/04/2019, 23:35 - Dikshita Kothari: Ya they went
03/04/2019, 23:55 - Dikshita Kothari: Hari Om

I apologise for missing the deadline last evening. But I was 'spooked' out of my wits and too petrified to string a coherent sentence together. Some children narrated frightening tales around a flickering candle in a wooden attic while other young rascals provided sound effects and special effects. I was completely unnerved. 

Yesterday, we found ourselves improvising all day. How can an adventure be a planned itinerary anyway!? The visit to the Blue Tea Factory went as per plan. The heart of tea is in the plucking and the soul of tea is in the steeping. The children learnt all this and more. 

Thereafter, an unplanned,  strenuous  hike led us to the Ramboda waterfall. We took a bath in it, at least the more daring ones did while the others watched and grappled with their diffidence and fears. I must mention Aanya here. She is doing something everyday that hitherto scared her. A mind stretched by new experiences cannot return to it's old dimensions. Aanya is a wondrous wonder everyday! Some complained of the moss, others of  the rocks hurting their feet. But the waterfall wouldn't sound as melodious if there weren't rocks in it's bed. All in all, everyone was delighted and wet without a change handy! 

Cycling at Nuwara Eliya was a spur of the moment decision too. The lake was shimmering. The tudor style cottages were bellowing smoke from their chimneys. The twilight was casting long shadows on the turf. The setting sun was outlining the clouds with silver linings. We chose to cycle a 5 km circuit and savour it all. One just can't be sad while riding a bike. All the riders returned grinning from ear to ear. 

In the meantime, the chefs of the day -  Bhanvi, Meghomala and Vanshika made assorted sandwiches that looked lavish and tasted sumptuous. What culinary connoisseurs!!! They were completely sold out and the kids were begging for more. 

We can proceed according to a planned itinerary strenuously trying to make life confirm to it's needs or we can adapt to whatever we meet and flow without effort. 

We chose the latter. 

Yesterday we heard the waterfall and birds and winds sing. 

Today the song of the waves is lulling us to sleep.

05/04/2019, 08:26 - Dikshita Kothari: Hess
05/04/2019, 08:27 - Dikshita Kothari: Hari Om
There is magic on this planet and it is contained in water. Little wonder why we immerse ourselves everyday. 

Rafting appears to be an adventure sport. We did chance the rapids and dance the tides.  But to us, it's a team building exercise too. The boat won't go if we all don't row together. So everytime the navigator yelled an instruction - "forward', "backward', "relax', "down"....we acted as one unit in perfect sync and harmony. For a while I watched Kanishk, Yana and Krishiv seated on my starboard side,  bang their oars and blame each other. But after only one heart-in-the-mouth rapid, the three stopped bickering and rowed better than the participants of Kerala's snake boat races. 

Alka facilitated a module on effective verbal and non-verbal communication skills. Through a fun game, she demonstrated how distortions occur and the message is lost. 

No sooner did we check into the Long Beach resort, than we changed and rushed to enjoy sea-bathing. The light was fast  failing and our time was marked. So we made the most of it albeit time moves differently at the beach. It doesn't move hour to hour, but mood to moment. Krishiv got a sound scolding for forgetting that he was human and not a merman. 

When the sun set in the distant horizon, the water babies made their way to the colossal swimming pool and played a tough match of water polo. 

At 7.30 pm the kids left to change into their party pants and LBDs. The hair gels and blush ons were brought out. The shirts were ironed and ironed again. One by one, the transformed princes and princesses assembled at the lobby all set to party. Alas, I can't tell you more. 

What happened at the Long Beach shall stay at the Long Beach. 

No one looks back at their life and remembers the nights they had plenty of sleep. Crazy nights make the best memories.

Deficit on sleep, surplus on memories...

Day 5 
Spectacular Sri Lanka
Travelicious memoirs
05/04/2019, 08:27 - Dikshita Kothari: Hari Om
A world without whales and dolphins wouldn't be much of a world at all. When you see them on TV, you're seeing close ups of these massive creatures and the music that's added gives you a certain feeling. In reality, the kids had partied late into the night and had barely shut eye when they were hauled out of bed and put on a boat that was bobbing up and down. They felt sick and the whale wasn't there on demand. They were forced to wash down an Avomine with tea/coffee that would keep the hangover and retching at bay. 

They were almost zoning out again when a gam of whales and a pod of dolphins stopped by to say hello. And then they were animated. Their souls and spirits took flight.

Alas, the Avomine had them under it's spell and they went through half the day in a trance. Doped and drugged,  they sleep walked through the Fort of Galle, a UNESCO world heritage site. 

Dr. Vidushi advised plenty of food and water. So by lunch time, they were more in their elements. 

But what truly jolted them awake was the boat cruise in a mangrove forest, the exotic  cinnamon island and the fish spa. Then there were squeals and screams so loud,  that all the black monkeys and cranes in the neighborhood were startled. Everyone yelled but 
Dikshita and Manasvi's shrieks had our ears ringing. Perhaps they'll win awards today for their caterwauls. 

The kids were sensitised to the plight of the turtles. And when they got to pet and love the hatchlings and the disabled ones, the bond was sealed forever. 

The kids were under the weather all day. Sanya succumbed and threw up in her vomit bag. Smart girl! 

But ask them, ' Whale you do it again? '

' Dolphinately!!!!! '

04/05/2019, 12:21 - Dikshita Kothari: I've been sitting awhile on this window seat with it smooth polished wooden top, close to the window.  The pot plants have been quivering plenty but  holding their perch. The trees beyond have been swaying dangerously but holding their own too. Wood is resilient, priceless in it's ageing and forever young, capable of being born a hundred times. Tiny rivulets have formed on the window panes distorting my view of the world. I have left the window a little ajar to feel the cold spray on my cheek and hand whenever the wind wills it. Storm or no storm, the city's rites of dawn must be underway. Newspaper boys must wheel past and toss their rolls. Milkmen, on cycles, their large tin cans clanging, must  ring door bells. The brisk, bowlegged, old men and women who work their arms as if dragging back their youth must be up and wonder what to do. On a clear day, boy servants take out the dogs of their masters. The dogs must be restlessly scraping at their front doors.  
The peril is almost passed. Man will bury and leave behind loss, sorrow, failure, misery and deprivation. If man didn't know this routine, he'd be so roasted and weighted, he couldn't move a single step. 
So let's talk of oases with springs of sherbet and doe-eyed houris...
It's a survival tool. It's a life skill.
